If there=E2=80=99s anyone with the proper perspective on Monday=E2=80=99s G=
olden Globes nominations, and the escalating fight behind the scenes of Hol=
lywood=E2=80=99s silliest awards show, it=E2=80=99s probably Luca Celada, t=
he Italian journalist for Rome=E2=80=99s Il Manifesto and a former board me=
mber of the Hollywood Foreign Press Association. Luca was one of the few HF=
PA-ers who vocally opposed the takeover by Todd Boehly and Jay Penske two y=
ears ago=E2=80=94a fraught deal plagued by conflicts of interest that has s=
ince led to crass profiteering, marginalized members, a state attorney gene=
ral inquiry related to its charitable arm, and a new call to reconsider the=
 transaction.

On nomination day, I had to give Luca a call. =E2=80=9CI was the main, and =
kind of lone, voice against the deal,=E2=80=9D Celada reminded me, referrin=
g to his 90 or so former HFPA
colleagues. =E2=80=9CThey all signed on enthusiastically, and now they=E2=
=80=99re telling me, Oh, you were right.=E2=80=9D

Exactly. We don=E2=80=99t need to rehash the whole saga, but if you=E2=80=
=99ve managed to purge the past few years of insane Globes news from your b=
rain=E2=80=A6 first, congrats=E2=80=A6 and second, here=E2=80=99s the botto=
m line: In 2021, a group of celebrity publicists, who hated the fact that t=
hey couldn=E2=80=99t control the foreign journalist group=E2=80=99s kooky p=
ress conferences, leveraged a post-George Floyd scandal over its lack of Bl=
ack members to spearhead an industry-wide boycott. Clout-hungry studio exec=
utives=E2=80=94who for decades, remember, had held zero reservations about =
courting Globes voters, despite their infamous starfucking and occasional s=
candals=E2=80=94quickly pledged to blackball the HFPA and its show. Noted s=
ocial justice warriors Tom Cruise and Scarlett Johansson even returned thei=
r Globes in disgust. Remember that? Sadly, the
Nobel Committee ignored their activism.

That performative protest, hilariously led by the nearly all-white P.R. fir=
ms, was resolved in part by a total overhaul of the HFPA. The process irone=
d out some legitimate issues with the membership. But it also gave Boehly, =
the owner of Globes producer Dick Clark Productions, control of the entire =
organization as its interim C.E.O. The billionaire investor and deal savant=
 then saw an opportunity to engineer a complex transaction and dissolve the=
 HFPA entirely=E2=80=94transforming the Globes from a charitable endeavor, =
like most awards shows, into a for-profit business.

Most of those former members=E2=80=94at least the ones who weren=E2=80=99t =
fired=E2=80=94became employees, paid $75,000 a year alongside a bunch of ne=
w, nonsalaried, non-HFPA voters, to quietly watch TV shows and movies year-=
round and deliver their annual nominations around the holidays, like Santa=
=E2=80=99s silent elves. Then they were expected to fall in line,
participating only in group Zoom interviews of talent, not private press co=
nferences. (Spielberg, for instance, wanted to do a press conference with t=
he HFPA back in 2022, but Boehly=E2=80=99s team blocked it.) All of this wa=
s done to =E2=80=9Cclean up=E2=80=9D the scandalous organization=E2=80=94an=
d, more importantly, to keep its teetering yet lucrative awards show on tel=
evision.

Boehly=E2=80=99s plan worked. The HFPA, facing a debilitating boycott despi=
te the fact that most of its members had done nothing wrong besides occasio=
nally wearing outrageous hats to the Globes, signed off on the deal. The pu=
blicists, who received what they really wanted via the demise of those in-p=
erson press conferences, quickly cozied up to Boehly. The 2023 test-run sho=
w=E2=80=94banished to a Tuesday by NBC=E2=80=94went off without a major hit=
ch, and CBS ended up taking the Globes for five years, albeit at a signific=
antly reduced license fee for a show that once was worth more than $60 mill=
ion a year.

In the process, Boehly booted the MRC production company, his previous part=
ners in Dick Clark, and brought in Penske Media Corp. as co-owner and opera=
tor of the business. That effectively made Jay Penske, the car racing heir =
and owner of the trade media outlets that cover the Globes, its day-to-day =
proprietor. (Usual disclosure: I=E2=80=99ve never worked for Penske, but I =
did work for Boehly when he owned The Hollywood Reporter and I was the edit=
or, and we=E2=80=99ve had a good relationship.)

Now, predictably, Boehly and especially Penske have sidelined those former =
HFPA members, disinviting them from their own awards show, whoring out thei=
r Globes brand for grubby events in the Middle East, and limiting access to=
 the talent interviews that helped the journalist members do their jobs=E2=
=80=94the entire reason the Hollywood Foreign Press Association was started=
 in the first place. =E2=80=9CThis is part of the privatization of everythi=
ng in the universe,=E2=80=9D
Celada told me. =E2=80=9CIn this specific case, by a corporation that just =
wanted to leverage the brand.=E2=80=9D

Conflicts of Interest

A group of those disgruntled HFPA-ers is even trying to convince California=
=E2=80=99s attorney general to revisit the 2022 dealmaking that gave Boehly=
 control, switched the HFPA to for-profit, and brought in Penske as a partn=
er. The anonymous group=E2=80=94I know who some of them are, but they feare=
d retaliation if I named them=E2=80=94engaged litigator Neville Johnson to =
send a 29-page legal brief to Joseph Zimring, the supervising deputy attorn=
ey general for the Charitable Trusts Section of Los Angeles.

The plea focuses on the rampant conflicts of interest: Boehly, who had long=
 wanted to buy the Globes, got himself named interim C.E.O. of the HFPA as =
a =E2=80=9Cvolunteer=E2=80=9D while he was running Eldridge, his investment=
 vehicle, which did end up buying the Globes. This despite competing offers=
 from investor Ron Burkle and a group
fronted by former Academy president Cheryl Boone Isaacs. That latter deal w=
ould have paid HFPA members $125,000 a year=E2=80=94far more than Boehly an=
d Penske. And I=E2=80=99m guessing that ownership by Boone Isaacs and her p=
artner, Yusef Jackson, both of whom are Black, probably would have done mor=
e to resolve the organization=E2=80=99s race scandal than two white male bi=
llionaires.

The legal brief also claims the HFPA members never agreed to Penske=E2=80=
=99s involvement in the Globes, which =E2=80=9Cwas ostensibly done to clean=
se the self-dealing and conflicts of interest presented by Boehly=E2=80=99s=
 status as both the purchaser and the seller in this transaction,=E2=80=9D =
according to the document, which I obtained. This despite the fact that Boe=
hly is still an investor in the Globes, as well as Penske=E2=80=99s media b=
usiness. =E2=80=9CThere=E2=80=99s no world in which any of us would have ag=
reed to being part of the Penske entertainment media monopoly,=E2=80=9D one=
 HFPA-er told me this week. The members
say they were sold out by HFPA president Helen Hoehne, who was =E2=80=9Crel=
entless=E2=80=9D in convincing colleagues to bless the deal and has been re=
warded as the well-paid and indefinite figurehead of the Golden Globes orga=
nization. They also claim that the group=E2=80=99s two officers responsible=
 for signing the 300-page deal saw only the first and last page, with every=
thing in the middle left out.

$(ad3_title) ( https://ad.doubleclick.net/ddm/trackclk/N485401.4235865PUCKN=
EWS/B32781436.409498353;dc_trk_aid=3D601608114;dc_trk_cid=3D226355417;dc_la=
t=3D;dc_rdid=3D;tag_for_child_directed_treatment=3D;tfua=3D;ltd=3D;dc_tdv=
=3D1?utm_campaign=3DWhat+I%27m+Hearing+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%2812%2F12%2F24%29&utm=
_content=3DWhat+I%27m+Hearing+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%2812%2F12%2F24%29&utm_medium=
=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a )

The brief then accuses Boehly and Penske of fraud and breach of fiduciary d=
uties in connection with the transaction=E2=80=94especially the part that w=
ill end the HFPA=E2=80=99s status as a nonprofit, tax-exempt organization, =
allowing for the Globes to be converted into a for-profit entity with a rel=
ated nonprofit arm for philanthropy that, at least so far, is giving less t=
o charity than it did presale. In California, when a nonprofit holds charit=
able assets it wishes to dissolve, it typically must obtain a =E2=80=9Cwaiv=
er of objection=E2=80=9D from the attorney general. The A.G.=E2=80=99s offi=
ce won=E2=80=99t grant one if it believes =E2=80=9Cthe proposed distributio=
n of assets is not aligned with the organization=E2=80=99s stated charitabl=
e purpose.=E2=80=9D

The A.G.=E2=80=99s office tentatively blessed the deal last year, but that =
was before the group of HFPA-ers raised these new issues. The
final approval is still pending, even after the HFPA board finally greenlit=
 its own dissolution in September amid a threatening letter from Eldridge=
=E2=80=99s lawyers at Sidley. (The A.G.=E2=80=99s office is now said to be =
in possession of that letter.) I asked Zimring about the status of the inqu=
iry. =E2=80=9CWe are currently reviewing the final request for a waiver of =
objection by the Hollywood Foreign Press Association,=E2=80=9D the A.G.=E2=
=80=99s office told me today. =E2=80=9CBeyond that, we have no further comm=
ent at this time.=E2=80=9D (Penske and Boehly also declined to comment on a=
ny of this.)

If the A.G. denies the dissolution, the Globes could effectively be back in=
 play=E2=80=94or at least that=E2=80=99s the argument, and it=E2=80=99s mad=
e more urgent because CBS has an out in its deal if there are any further c=
ontroversies. But it=E2=80=99s a long shot. After all, the members signed t=
he deal. They had lawyers representing them, although with the Globes it wa=
s always murky whose interests were being served. The
charitable elements of the HFPA and its foundation might draw the interest =
of politicians, but the notoriously problematic Globes voters are hardly sy=
mpathetic victims here. It=E2=80=99s a tough situation.

=E2=80=9CIndustry Rot=E2=80=9D

As all this is going on, I keep hearing complaints from the awards communit=
y about the tacky profiteering of the New Globes. Sure, the entire Oscar se=
ason is a gross cash grab rooted in vanity and insecurity, and Penske=E2=80=
=99s sales apparatus wasn=E2=80=99t exactly known for class or discretion b=
efore the Globes acquisition. But the show now charges thousands of dollars=
 to post films and TV shows on its screening platform, something the HFPA n=
ever did.

Costs associated with tickets and everything else Globes-related have also =
gone way up. Right before last January=E2=80=99s show, several top executiv=
es were informed that their usual seats in the pit with their talent had be=
en eliminated due to an extended stage, prompting a last-minute scramble.

And earlier this year, Penske=E2=80=99s sales team pimped access to Globes =
voters via sponsored
=E2=80=9Cupscale dinners=E2=80=9D thrown by Variety, which he owns, until I=
 and others reported ( https://puck.news/newsletter_content/what-im-hearing=
-the-sarandos-soapbox-globes-pimps/?utm_campaign=3DWhat+I%27m+Hearing+-+SUB=
SCRIBERS+%2812%2F12%2F24%29&utm_content=3DWhat+I%27m+Hearing+-+SUBSCRIBERS+=
%2812%2F12%2F24%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_t=
erm=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ) on it and the plan was dropped. At the time, sev=
eral Globes voters told me they would have refused to participate=E2=80=94b=
ut, of course, as at-will employees, Penske could fire them at any time for=
 not doing his bidding.

Basically, the company now limits access to Globes voters and then charges =
for it wherever it can. This year, Penske has been launching more Globes-re=
lated events, like a sponsored night-before dinner for the honorary awards =
and a sponsored =E2=80=9Cofficial first time nominee luncheon,=E2=80=9D as =
the invite reads, attempting to take a page from the Academy=E2=80=99s
Nominees Luncheon. (Remember, the Oscars are awarded by a nonprofit arts or=
ganization comprised of the people who make and market movies. The Globes a=
re=E2=80=A6 not.)

Penske has also staged tacky new Globes-branded =E2=80=9Ccelebrations,=E2=
=80=9D giving the perpetually carpet-ready Sharon Stone a =E2=80=9CGolden G=
lobes Icon=E2=80=9D award ( https://goldenglobes.com/articles/sharon-stone-=
given-first-ever-golden-globes-intl-icon-award/?utm_campaign=3DWhat+I%27m+H=
earing+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%2812%2F12%2F24%29&utm_content=3DWhat+I%27m+Hearing+-+=
SUBSCRIBERS+%2812%2F12%2F24%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcusto=
mer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a )in Turkey in August, and creating an =
=E2=80=9COmar Sharif Award=E2=80=9D in Egypt. A Globes-branded party for th=
e London Film Festival featured a paid speech by OGM Pictures, a Turkish co=
mpany, which one attendee told me caused a lot of eye-rolling in the room.

It=E2=80=99s all low-rent and off-putting, but I
know, this has always been an inside joke of an awards show that somehow be=
came a globally recognized brand. Even Celada, who refused to sign an N.D.A=
=2E and was purged from the group of HF=
PA-ers, has remained one of those non-=
HFPA voters, serving in the nonsalaried group so he can still receive scree=
ners and influence the awards race. =E2=80=9CSaudi money, Qatari money=E2=
=80=94the Penske model, this is what these guys do,=E2=80=9D he said. =E2=
=80=9CTo me, it not only has nothing to do with awards or film criticism, o=
r cinephilia, but it actually is destructive.=E2=80=9D

To a point. Despite the backstage fight, the industry seems to have decided=
 the Globes are back. Monday=E2=80=99s nominations were fine. Penske last y=
ear added a sixth slot in every category to help prevent egregious snubs=E2=
=80=94and generate more demand for tickets=E2=80=94and the nominations were=
n=E2=80=99t embarrassing. The publicists are now pretending as if nothing h=
appened, even reaching out to the same HFPA members they defenestrated as i=
f
they=E2=80=99re all friends now. As evidenced by the earnest interviews and=
 celebratory quotes, the talent still cares about the Globes=E2=80=94or at =
least everyone is savvy enough to kiss the ring on the way to what they rea=
lly want: an Oscar.

So maybe it=E2=80=99s a fitting Hollywood ending that the Globes have been =
plundered by two billionaires who positioned themselves as saviors. The ind=
ustry got what it deserved=E2=80=94though the next step could be a lawsuit.=
 As sad as this is for the sidelined HFPA members who had shepherded an eve=
nt for decades that, even with all its silliness and scandals, benefited th=
e entire industry and supported a small-time group of foreign journalists, =
it=E2=80=99s a gross yet ultimately on-brand evolution in modern Hollywood.=
 After all, Luca told me, =E2=80=9CThis is all indicative of industry rot.=
=E2=80=9D

See you Monday,
Matt

