          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">If there=E2=80=99s =
anyone with the proper perspective on Monday=E2=80=99s Golden Globes nomina=
tions, and the escalating fight behind the scenes of Hollywood=E2=80=99s si=
lliest awards show, it=E2=80=99s probably <b>Luca Celada</b>, the Italian j=
ournalist for Rome=E2=80=99s <i>Il Manifesto</i> and a former board member =
of the Hollywood Foreign Press Association. Luca was one of the few HFPA-er=
s who vocally opposed the takeover by <b>Todd Boehly</b> and <b>Jay Penske =
</b>two years ago=E2=80=94a fraught deal plagued by conflicts of interest t=
hat has since led to crass profiteering, marginalized members, a state atto=
rney general inquiry related to its charitable arm, and a new call to recon=
sider the transaction. <br/><br/>On nomination day, I had to give Luca a ca=
ll. =E2=80=9CI was the main, and kind of lone, voice against the deal,=E2=
=80=9D Celada reminded me, referring to his 90 or so former HFPA
colleagues. =E2=80=9CThey all signed on enthusiastically, and now they=E2=
=80=99re telling me, <i>Oh, you were right</i>.=E2=80=9D  <br/> <br/>Exactl=
y. We don=E2=80=99t need to rehash the whole saga, but if you=E2=80=99ve ma=
naged to purge the past few years of insane Globes news from your brain=E2=
=80=A6 first, congrats=E2=80=A6 and second, here=E2=80=99s the bottom line:=
 In 2021, a group of celebrity publicists, who hated the fact that they cou=
ldn=E2=80=99t control the foreign journalist group=E2=80=99s kooky press co=
nferences, leveraged a post-<b>George Floyd</b> scandal over its lack of Bl=
ack members to spearhead an industry-wide boycott. Clout-hungry studio exec=
utives=E2=80=94who <i>for decades</i>, remember, had held <i>zero</i> reser=
vations about courting Globes voters, despite their infamous starfucking an=
d occasional scandals=E2=80=94quickly pledged to blackball the HFPA and its=
 show. Noted social justice warriors <b>Tom Cruise</b> and <b>Scarlett Joha=
nsson </b>even <i>returned</i> their Globes in disgust. Remember <i>that</i=
>? Sadly, the
Nobel Committee ignored their activism.  <br/><br/>That performative protes=
t, hilariously led by the nearly all-white P.R. firms, was resolved in part=
 by a total overhaul of the HFPA. The process ironed out some legitimate is=
sues with the membership. But it also gave Boehly, the owner of Globes prod=
ucer Dick Clark Productions, control of the entire organization as its inte=
rim C.E.O. The billionaire investor and deal savant then saw an opportunity=
 to engineer a complex transaction and dissolve the HFPA entirely=E2=80=94t=
ransforming the Globes from a charitable endeavor, like most awards shows, =
into a <i>for-profit</i> business. <br/><br/>Most of those former members=
=E2=80=94at least the ones who weren=E2=80=99t fired=E2=80=94became employe=
es, paid $75,000 a year alongside a bunch of new, nonsalaried, non-HFPA vot=
ers, to quietly watch TV shows and movies year-round and deliver their annu=
al nominations around the holidays, like Santa=E2=80=99s silent elves. Then=
 they were expected to fall in line,
participating only in group Zoom interviews of talent, not private press co=
nferences. (<b>Spielberg</b>, for instance, wanted to do a press conference=
 with the HFPA back in 2022, but Boehly=E2=80=99s team blocked it.) All of =
this was done to =E2=80=9Cclean up=E2=80=9D the scandalous organization=E2=
=80=94and, more importantly, to keep its teetering yet lucrative awards sho=
w on television.<br/> <br/>Boehly=E2=80=99s plan worked. The HFPA, facing a=
 debilitating boycott despite the fact that most of its members had done no=
thing wrong besides occasionally wearing outrageous hats to the Globes, sig=
ned off on the deal. The publicists, who received what they really wanted v=
ia the demise of those in-person press conferences, quickly cozied up to Bo=
ehly. The 2023 test-run show=E2=80=94banished to a Tuesday by NBC=E2=80=94w=
ent off without a major hitch, and CBS ended up taking the Globes for five =
years, albeit at a <i>significantly</i> reduced license fee for a show that=
 once was worth more than $60 million a year.<br/>
<br/>In the process, Boehly booted the MRC production company, his previous=
 partners in Dick Clark, and brought in Penske Media Corp. as co-owner and =
operator of the business. That effectively made <b>Jay Penske</b>, the car =
racing heir and owner of the trade media outlets that <i>cover</i> the Glob=
