x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">The brief then accu=
ses Boehly and Penske of fraud and breach of fiduciary duties in connection=
 with the transaction=E2=80=94especially the part that will end the HFPA=E2=
=80=99s status as a nonprofit, tax-exempt organization, allowing for the Gl=
obes to be converted into a for-profit entity with a related nonprofit arm =
for philanthropy that, at least so far, is giving less to charity than it d=
id presale. In California, when a nonprofit holds charitable assets it wish=
es to dissolve, it typically must obtain a =E2=80=9Cwaiver of objection=E2=
=80=9D from the attorney general. The A.G.=E2=80=99s office won=E2=80=99t g=
rant one if it believes =E2=80=9Cthe proposed distribution of assets is not=
 aligned with the organization=E2=80=99s stated charitable purpose.=E2=80=
=9D  <br/> <br/>The A.G.=E2=80=99s office tentatively blessed the deal last=
 year, but that was before the group of HFPA-ers raised these new issues. T=
he
final approval is still pending, even after the HFPA board finally greenlit=
 its own dissolution in September amid a threatening letter from Eldridge=
=E2=80=99s lawyers at Sidley. (The A.G.=E2=80=99s office is now said to be =
in possession of that letter.) I asked Zimring about the status of the inqu=
iry. =E2=80=9CWe are currently reviewing the final request for a waiver of =
objection by the Hollywood Foreign Press Association,=E2=80=9D the A.G.=E2=
=80=99s office told me today. =E2=80=9CBeyond that, we have no further comm=
ent at this time.=E2=80=9D (Penske and Boehly also declined to comment on a=
ny of this.)<br/> <br/>If the A.G. denies the dissolution, the Globes could=
 effectively be back in play=E2=80=94or at least that=E2=80=99s the argumen=
t, and it=E2=80=99s made more urgent because CBS has an out in its deal if =
there are any further controversies. But it=E2=80=99s a long shot. After al=
l, the members signed the deal. They had lawyers representing them, althoug=
h with the Globes it was always murky whose interests were being served. Th=
e
charitable elements of the HFPA and its foundation might draw the interest =
of politicians, but the notoriously problematic Globes voters are hardly sy=
mpathetic victims here. It=E2=80=99s a tough situation.<br/></td>
