=80=9CTo me, it not only has nothing to do with awards or film criticism, o=
r cinephilia, but it actually is destructive.=E2=80=9D<br/> <br/>To a point=
=2E Despite the backstage fight, the in=
dustry seems to have decided the Globe=
s are back. Monday=E2=80=99s nominations were fine. Penske last year added =
a sixth slot in every category to help prevent egregious snubs=E2=80=94and =
generate more demand for tickets=E2=80=94and the nominations weren=E2=80=99=
t embarrassing. The publicists are now pretending as if nothing happened, e=
ven reaching out to the same HFPA members they defenestrated as if
they=E2=80=99re all friends now. As evidenced by the earnest interviews and=
 celebratory quotes, the talent still cares about the Globes=E2=80=94or at =
least everyone is savvy enough to kiss the ring on the way to what they rea=
lly want: an Oscar.<br/> <br/>So maybe it=E2=80=99s a fitting Hollywood end=
ing that the Globes have been plundered by two billionaires who positioned =
themselves as saviors. The industry got what it deserved=E2=80=94though the=
 next step could be a lawsuit. As sad as this is for the sidelined HFPA mem=
bers who had shepherded an event for decades that, even with all its sillin=
ess and scandals, benefited the entire industry and supported a small-time =
group of foreign journalists, it=E2=80=99s a gross yet ultimately on-brand =
evolution in modern Hollywood. After all, Luca told me, =E2=80=9CThis is al=
l indicative of industry rot.=E2=80=9D   <br/></td>
